The film “Moneyball” is based on Michael Lewis’s 2003 nonfiction book of
the same name, an account of the Oakland Athletics baseball team’s 2002
season and their general manager’s attempts to assemble a competitive
team.

We want to understand historically how efficient teams are at spending
money and getting wins in return. In the case of Moneyball, one would
expect that Oakland was not much more efficient than other teams in
their spending before 2000, were much more efficient between 2000 and
2005, and by then other teams may have caught up. Your job in this
project is to see if this is true.

Load the **tidyverse** and **Lahman** libraries. (2 pts.)

``` r
library(tidyverse)
```

Let’s begin by filtering our datasets to contain only data between the
years 1990 and 2015, inclusive. We should also store this filtered data
in a new dataset to avoid mutating our original datasets. Name the new
datasets “teams”, and “salaries” (no capitals). (10 pts.)

``` r
s_teams <- filter(Teams, yearID >= 1990, yearID <= 2015 )
s_salaries <- filter(Salaries, yearID >= 1990, yearID <= 2015)
```

### Problem 1

Use the group\_by() and summarize() functions, along with the %\>%
operator, to calculate the yearly payroll for all teams in the
“salaries” dataset. Save this to a new dataset called
“by\_teams\_year”. (8 pts.)

``` r
by_teams_year <- s_salaries %>%
  group_by(teamID, yearID) %>%
  summarize(
    payroll = sum(salary, na.rm = TRUE) 
  )
```

### Problem 3

Let’s create a new measurement unit that summarizes how efficiently each
team spends its money, every year.

**We’ll use the number of wins a team can get (W) per dollar spent
(payroll)**

wpd = W / payroll

wpd stands for “wins per dollar”

Use the group\_by() and summarize() functions to calculate the number of
wins per dollar spent on payroll by each team, each year. Save this to a
new dataset called “wpd\_dataset” (10 pts.)

``` r
wpd_dataset <- simple_joined %>%
  group_by(teamID, yearID) %>%
  summarize(wpd = W / payroll)
```

### Problem 4

Using the result of Problem 3, calculate the average number of wins per
dollar spent *by all teams* for each year. Again, use the group\_by()
and summarize() functions. Save this to a new dataset called
“avg\_wpd\_dataset”. (8 pts.)

``` r
avg_wpd_dataset <- wpd_dataset %>%
  group_by(yearID)%>%
  summarize(avg_wpd = mean(wpd))
```

With the result of Problem 4, now we can approximate the number of wins
we would expect each team to get given their payroll, and then see how
many more (or less) wins they had compared to this expectation. Take a
moment to try to understand this concept, it is VERY important.

Note: this is a naive version of linear regression that we’ll see in
better detail later in the semester.

##### Step 3

Use the mutate() function to add a new column to your dataset with the
name “expected\_wins” that equals “payroll” times “avg\_wpd” (5 pts.)

``` r
calculations <- mutate(calculations, expected_wins = payroll * avg_wpd)
```

We’re almost done\! All that’s left for us to do is compare our
calculations for expected number of wins with the actual number of wins.

##### Step 4

Use the mutate() function to add a new column to your dataset with the
name “residual\_wins” that equals “W” - “expected\_wins”. (5 pts.)

``` r
calculations <- mutate(calculations, residual_wins = W - expected_wins)
```

Great job\! Go ahead and run the code chunk below. If you have done
everything correctly, you should see a plot comparing how efficiently
the Oakland Athletics, New York Yankees, New York Mets, and Boston Red
Sox used their money from 1990 - 2015.

``` r
calculations %>%
  filter(teamID %in% c("OAK", "NYA", "NYN", "BOS")) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = yearID, y = residual_wins, color = teamID)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
```
